The US Supreme Court debated the legality of the death penalty for criminals under 18, with international attention on the Simmons case.
Arguments focused on whether minors should face execution, with concerns about deterrence and maturity.
Justices considered a potential national consensus against juvenile executions, similar to the ban on executing the mentally retarded.
The court's decision could impact thousands of cases and the federal sentencing system.
The debate also touched on other legal issues, including drug laws and racial segregation in prisons.
The justices' decision will have far-reaching implications for criminal law in the US.
